    # [Scene: New Seawall Area | Afternoon — Three Months Later]
    hide maya_corvin
    hide rafi_odeh

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant conversations translated to a soft murmur through comms, the steady beeping of monitoring stations]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Mid-tempo strings; a sense of forward motion with a low undercurrent of unease]
    "Months fold into procedural checks. The city's dashboards glow with tidy graphs: projected risk reduced by a measurable percentage, maintenance schedules logged, investor briefings stamped 'on track.' Elias Kahn stands at the municipal oversight desk, an organized knot of papers and a tablet timelined in careful compromises."
    show elias_kahn at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kahn "We got the community seats. We got transparency feeds and inspection days. I'm pushing for stricter definitions on 'nonperforming' — we can't let them axe corridors because a model says so once."
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "Models are snapshots, Eli. They can't measure what a plaza means."

    elias_kahn "I know. I'm trying to hold both. If I push too hard the board delays work and we lose momentum; if I don’t, we hollow protections. I keep thinking about the arbitration clause."
    "There's fatigue threaded through his steady voice. You see it in the way his fingers curl around a coffee cup like a lifeline. He wants to be bolder. He is learning the language of compromise —"
    "not because he likes it, but because the deadlines demand someone translate empathy into legally binding steps."
    "Dr. Sima's projections arrive by email, labeled 'stress test results.' In the late hours you sit cross-legged on the rooftop nursery and read them under solar lamp light. The numbers are honest and brutal: the modules"
    "perform as designed, but under extreme, repeated stress scenarios, corridors with lower immediate 'performance' indicators are flagged. The triage logic is merciless."

    "Your internal monologue spins maps of possibility: each "flag" is a footnote where culture, ritual, and memory might be excised for statistical efficiency. The humidity clings; earth smells faintly sweet under the lamp. You flip to the last page and find a recommended mitigation that reads like a compromise" "Adaptive replanting and community stewardship recommended to offset corridor attrition."
    "You send the message to Camila 'Kai' Navarro and Elias Kahn both, fingers moving faster than your confidence. The reply that comes back first is mercantile, not cruel:"

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "We can pilot the adaptive replanting in zone four. But if the sensors detect 'underperformance' beyond threshold three times in a quarter, we will need to re-route modules to prioritize system integrity."
    "You stare at the conditional language until the lamp blurs. It is protection, and it is a precise chisel."
    # [Scene: Cultural Plaza | Early Morning — Demolition Notice]
    hide elias_kahn
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The low hum of standby engines, a PA announcement in the distance; the distant laugh of a child that sounds small against steel]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet piano, a single mournful motif]

    "A municipal posting has been nailed to the base of the statue you fought to save. The words are bureaucratic and final" "Marine Access Point Construction — Immediate Allocation Approved."
    "Lio stands by the fence, hoodie smeared with new paint, and stares at a section of the mural — his mural — already marked with spray paint lines. He looks younger than he did three months ago; something in his shoulders has slumped."
    show lio_corvin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lio_corvin "They say it's for safety. Mayor's office says it reduces crowding by X percent during mass-egress scenarios."
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "So what we call 'culture' is a variable now. A percentage to be optimized."

    lio_corvin "You took this on, Maya. You chose to sign. I get that. But watching them mark my mural like it's a construction grid—"
    "You reach the fence and press your palms to the mesh. The metal reverberates faintly under your hands. Your mouth wants to form all the things you told yourself were worth the trade-off: saved homes, reduced risk, more seasons. Instead you get the blunt, aching concrete of loss."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro appears at your side, notebook in hand. She doesn't explain away the markings; she doesn't have to. Her eyes are a careful gray today."

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "We kept commitments. We scheduled community consultations. We carved out inspection days."

    maya_corvin "You carved. You didn't keep everything. The plaza—"

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "The plaza was in the design compromises. We argued to keep the fountain and a green corridor. Legal insisted on the access point for redundancy. There were alternatives that delayed the whole project by months."
    "Her voice is not sharp; it's factual. It's the tone someone uses when listing sacrifices made in a war they thought necessary."

    maya_corvin "Months would have been months of gates open to the sea. People could have lost roofs. Babies could have been swept. You know that."

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "I do. I also know tearing up a meeting place is not just moving concrete. It's moving memory. We made a call. We tried to preserve as much as we could."
    "The pause stretches between you like a cable. Neither of you is willing to name the gulf outright. You both know where you stood when the choice was made; you both still stand there now, side by side and not unified."
    "Elias Kahn arrives, breath thick from the climb, his municipal badge catching the morning haze."
    show elias_kahn at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kahn "I pushed for delayed demolition, at least until we could set up a temporary cultural space. Budget board wouldn't greenlight it. They say 'temporary' too often when a line item looks small."

    maya_corvin "Temporary is where things go to die."

    elias_kahn "I know. I argued for a clause to guarantee maintenance funding for the community-led spaces. The clause is there. The funding is contingent on annual approvals and matching municipal allocations."
    "You stare at him, wanting to be angrier than you are. The bureaucracy has softened into a thousand polite refusals."

    menu:
        "Climb over the fence and touch Lio's mural":
            "You hoist yourself over the mesh with clumsy certainty and lay your hand on the bright paint. The texture is rough; the colors are still wet. Lio steps closer, and for a second the world is only the two of you and that stubborn, defiant color."
        "Hold back and take a photo to document the before":
            "You raise the camera slowly and frame the mural against the spray-painted lines. The image is clinical and true; you send it to Rafi and Dr. Sima with one finger. It's evidence for later pleadings, and it feels like a small, impotent weapon."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue the scene"
    "The demolition begins with a polite clank and a mechanical groan — not heroic, not cinematic. A jackhammer bites into the plaza's edge; a crane lifts and angles a slab away like a butcher separating muscle"
    "from bone. People with hard hats move with ritualized efficiency, and the plaza's open belly reveals the earth's rawness: soil, old pipes, stories folded into layers of material."
    "You think of the morning the Low Row first taught you how to tidewalk — how elders mapped safe paths by memory, not by algorithm. You think of the lantern nights where neighbors held hands across"
    "the promenade to celebrate harvests of rooftop gardens. Those practices are not quantifiable in stress tests. They are the grammar of a place."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro watches the demolition. For a second, unguarded, she pinches the porcelain pendant hidden at her collar. You see the flash of something private — a childhood she isn't ready to sacrifice to the"
    "ledger. Her shoulders twitch as if she wants to explain and cannot find the concession that would make the scrape of heavy metal feel less like loss."

    maya_corvin "Did the arbitration clause ever have a line about cultural loss?"

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "Not explicitly. Cultural loss is hard to quantify. We used mitigation language: 'adaptive cultural programming' — funds, timelines, community input. But if 'underperformance' triggers reconfiguration, maintenance budgets shrink. It's messy."

    elias_kahn "We can keep fighting within the board. We can try to attach enforceable maintenance commitments. Legal can attempt to bind budgets for X years."
    "You want to believe him. You want to think that paperwork and persistence can hold back an eroding tide of corporate leverage. But the months have taught you the rhythm: investor priorities shift; legal language finds cracks; 'temporary' becomes a date on a calendar that moves without human protest."
    "Your stubborn empathy — the thing that made you both stubborn and beloved — feels, in this place, like both a shield and a wound. You had wanted to save your neighborhood; in the narrow ledger"
    "of lives saved, you did. But something else fell through the gaps: the intangible anchorage that taught people how to be neighbors."
    hide lio_corvin
    hide maya_corvin
    hide elias_kahn

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Waves now break against engineered stone; the old gentle lap replaced with a mechanical thud]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slow, melancholic swell; strings carry a single minor chord]
    "You stand on the remnant of the plaza, the scent of dust and salt mixing in the air. The partial seawall gleams where sunlight hits; it is functional and beautiful in an austerely correct way. Children"
    "play near a newly installed drainage channel and kick up water that runs cleanly into an intake grate. The immediate threat — the violent, nightly flooding that once stole sleep from Low Row — has diminished."
    "But when you turn back, you see the faces of your neighborhood in a new light: grateful, disoriented, and braided through with a small, private grief. Lio avoids meeting your eyes. Rafi pretends to check a clipboard. Elias Kahn looks at you as if holding two truths at once."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro steps closer, close enough for the salt in her hair to brush your cheek. There is a private respect between you now — a complex, unreadable face of affection folded into professional alignment."

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "You did the hard thing. You mobilized people. You held the community line when it mattered. I didn't expect to like you when we started this."
    show maya_corvin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "You didn't expect to like me. You didn't expect to be on my side."

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "I didn't expect the shape of the thing to look like this. I thought we could keep more."

    maya_corvin "More is a greedy word. Maybe it was always a collection of small asks we couldn't make stick."
    "Silence stretches, not empty but full of the debris of decisions. You want to say the unavoidably human thing: that you loved the idea of her. You want to say that love and corporate clauses don't mix cleanly. You don't say either."
    "Your pulse slows to a steady thrum. The arousal of action — the mid-tempo busyness of months of construction and meetings — begins to recede into a raw, negative valence: grief wrapped in practical relief."
    "You think of the compass at your chest, useless for direction, faithful as a charm. You think of all the small ceremonies the neighborhood conducted to mark survival. You think of the cultural plaza's half-finished fountain and the way the light pools there now, odd and new."
    "You exhale, and for the first time in months, let the full weight of the trade settle in."
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano resolves into a single held note that fades]
    "Page-Turn Moment"
    "You walk the promenade's edge alone and watch the seawall blot out part of the horizon you grew up with. It keeps more people dry. It takes some stories away. You are not naïve enough to"
    "believe purity always wins, nor cynical enough to think compromise absolves pain. The work ahead is different from the one you imagined — it will be maintenance, vigilance, legal wrangling, and small acts of remembrance stitched"
    "into the cracks. You feel both vindicated that lives were spared and betrayed that 'temporary' is a word that eats at meaning. The chapter closes not with a single verdict but with the steady, complicated knowledge"
    "that protection arrived with losses you must name aloud if they are to survive."

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
